        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
              <fr:month>4</fr:month>
              <fr:day>15</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/006P/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>006P</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/lectures/006P/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Building up more complex proofs">Building up more complex proofs</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>        Natural deduction systems allow you to build up more complex proofs from less complex ones by using rules.
        Rules in natural deduction systems add on to the bottom of existing proofs, yielding new conclusions.
        (Sometimes, they also fiddle with the top of existing proofs; more on that in a moment.)
        Although they're called "rules", they really function more like <html:em>building blocks</html:em>.
        Proofs are built up out of rules.
</html:p>
            <html:p>        For each of our connectives, NJ includes two kinds of rules: <html:em>introduction rules</html:em> and <html:em>elimination rules</html:em>.
        Introduction rules for a connective let us draw a conclusion with that connective as its main connective.
        Elimination rules for a connective let us take an existing proof whose conclusion has that connective as its main connective, and build further from it.
</html:p>
            <html:p>        For example, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\land ]]></fr:tex> has one introduction rule and two elimination rules.
        Here they are:
</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>4</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>15</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/007A/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>007A</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/007A/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Conjunction introduction and elimination:">Conjunction introduction and elimination:</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
                  <fr:resource hash="bf25bab590601242e79d3a30a6c5318d">
                    <fr:resource-content>
                      <html:img src="/lectures/bf25bab590601242e79d3a30a6c5318d.svg" />
                    </fr:resource-content>
                    <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[
  \usepackage {bussproofs}
  \newcommand {\DP }{\DisplayProof }
  ]]></fr:resource-source>
                    <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
            \AxiomC{\ensuremath{A\vphantom{|}}}
            \AxiomC{\ensuremath{B\vphantom{|}}}
            \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \land  I:\quad }}
            \BinaryInfC{\ensuremath{A \land  B\vphantom{|}}}
            \DP
            \hskip 1cm
            \AxiomC{\ensuremath{A \land  B\vphantom{|}}}
            \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \land  E_l:\quad }}
            \UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{A\vphantom{|}}}
            \DP
            \hskip 1cm
            \AxiomC{\ensuremath{A \land  B\vphantom{|}}}
            \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \land  E_r:\quad }}
            \UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{B\vphantom{|}}}
            \DP
        ]]></fr:resource-source>
                  </fr:resource>
                </html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>You should read these rules as follows.
        First, take <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\land  E_l]]></fr:tex>.
        This says that if you already have a proof with a conclusion of the form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \land  B]]></fr:tex>---that is, a conclusion that is a conjunction---then you can extend that proof at the bottom with a step of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\land  E_l]]></fr:tex>, giving you a proof of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.
        (As always, remember that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>, and such are not sentences!
        They are used here in presenting the rule to let you know that you can do this <html:em>whatever</html:em> conjunction you have.)
</html:p>
            <html:p>        So, for example, take our earlier proof: just the plain assumption of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \land  (q \rightarrow  r)]]></fr:tex>.
        Since this is a proof whose conclusion is a conjunction, we can extend it via <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\land  E_l]]></fr:tex>.
        That would give us the following proof:</html:p>
            <html:p>
              <fr:resource hash="55af88a92d7313b2398a3587a7134f5a">
                <fr:resource-content>
                  <html:img src="/lectures/55af88a92d7313b2398a3587a7134f5a.svg" />
                </fr:resource-content>
                <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[
  \usepackage {bussproofs}
  \newcommand {\DP }{\DisplayProof }
  ]]></fr:resource-source>
                <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[   \AxiomC{\ensuremath{p \land  (q \rightarrow  r)\vphantom{|}}}
            \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \land  E_l:\quad }}
            \UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{p\vphantom{|}}}
            \DP
        ]]></fr:resource-source>
              </fr:resource>
            </html:p>
            <html:p>This is a proof with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \land  (q \rightarrow  r)]]></fr:tex> at the top and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> at the bottom.
        You should read it as saying that if we take <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \land  (q \rightarrow  r)]]></fr:tex> for granted, to explore what follows from it, then we can find that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> follows from it.
</html:p>
            <html:p>        The rule <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\land  E_r]]></fr:tex>  is very similar, but it allows us to conclude the right component of the conjunction rather than the left.
        So a new example proof using <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\land  E_r]]></fr:tex> might look like this:</html:p>
            <html:p>
              <fr:resource hash="87c5dc45962cd695bf8dc8820bf407a5">
                <fr:resource-content>
                  <html:img src="/lectures/87c5dc45962cd695bf8dc8820bf407a5.svg" />
                </fr:resource-content>
                <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[
  \usepackage {bussproofs}
  \newcommand {\DP }{\DisplayProof }
  ]]></fr:resource-source>
                <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[

            \AxiomC{\ensuremath{(p \lor  q) \land  (r \rightarrow  \neg  r)\vphantom{|}}}
            \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \land  E_r:\quad }}
            \UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{r \rightarrow  \neg  r\vphantom{|}}}
            \DP
            ]]></fr:resource-source>
              </fr:resource>
            </html:p>
            <html:p>This proof begins by assuming <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(p \lor  q) \land  (r \rightarrow  \neg  r)]]></fr:tex>, and then extends this assumption with a step of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\land  E_r]]></fr:tex>, concluding its right component <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r \rightarrow  \neg  r]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
            <html:p>        The rule <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\land  I]]></fr:tex> is only a bit more complex.
        Since it has two sentences above the line, this rule combines <html:em>two</html:em> preexisting proofs into a new one.
        It can be used to combine any two proofs: if the conclusion of the left proof is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and the conclusion of the right proof is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>, then the conclusion of the resulting proof will be <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \land  B]]></fr:tex>.
        For example, we can use this rule to combine the two most recent example proofs into a larger proof, giving us this:</html:p>
            <html:p>
              <fr:resource hash="466604efa52a1cd7262d1d8898e8fcfd">
                <fr:resource-content>
                  <html:img src="/lectures/466604efa52a1cd7262d1d8898e8fcfd.svg" />
                </fr:resource-content>
                <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[
  \usepackage {bussproofs}
  \newcommand {\DP }{\DisplayProof }
  ]]></fr:resource-source>
                <fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
        
            \AxiomC{\ensuremath{p \land  (q \rightarrow  r)\vphantom{|}}}
            \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \land  E_l:\quad }}
            \UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{p\vphantom{|}}}
            \AxiomC{\ensuremath{(p \lor  q) \land  (r \rightarrow  \neg  r)\vphantom{|}}}
            \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \land  E_r:\quad }}
            \UnaryInfC{\ensuremath{r \rightarrow  \neg  r\vphantom{|}}}
            \LeftLabel{\ensuremath{\scriptsize  \land  I:\quad }}
            \BinaryInfC{\ensuremath{p \land  (r \rightarrow  \neg  r)\vphantom{|}}}
            \DP
            ]]></fr:resource-source>
              </fr:resource>
            </html:p>
            <html:p>        This proof takes two things for granted: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \land  (q \rightarrow  r)]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(p \lor  q) \land  (r \rightarrow  \neg  r)]]></fr:tex>.
        Supposing these things, it shows that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \land  (r \rightarrow  \neg  r)]]></fr:tex> follows.
</html:p>
            <html:p>        I'll call <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \land  (q \rightarrow  r)]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(p \lor  q) \land  (r \rightarrow  \neg  r)]]></fr:tex> the <html:strong>open assumptions</html:strong> of this proof, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \land  (r \rightarrow  \neg  r)]]></fr:tex> its <html:strong>conclusion</html:strong>. 
        (We'll see what's "open" about open assumptions in just a moment.)
        Try not to get too confused by the word "conclusion": we're now using this word in two ways.
        In one use, which you've had for a few weeks now, it picks out a particular place in an <html:em>argument</html:em>.
        In this new use I'm telling you about now, it picks out a particular place in a <html:em>proof</html:em>.
        Since arguments and proofs are different kinds of things, these are two different uses. 
        The uses are very similar, though, and as we'll see next time they're also closely related.
        So I think it's not too awful to use the same word for both.
        (Do note, though, that I'm definitely <html:em>not</html:em> using the same word for the open assumptions of a proof and the premises of an argument.
        More on that, too, next time.)
        </html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
